# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1906-chicago-cubs-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1906-chicago-cubs-season/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1871 Chicago White Stockings season** was the second season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the first in the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players and the first at Union Base-Ball Grounds.
[src:1906-chicago-cubs-season/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] With the debut of the first professional baseball league, the National Association, the Chicago franchise joined up as the "White Stockings." The team went 19–9 and finished second in the league standings.
[src:1906-chicago-cubs-season/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] Pitcher George Zettlein started all 28 of Chicago's games and led the NA with a 2.73 earned run average.
[src:1906-chicago-cubs-season/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] Near the end of the season, the team lost its stadiums and equipment when the Great Chicago Fire hit the city.
[src:1906-chicago-cubs-season/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] The team was able to finish out the season on the road, but had to drop out of the league while the city attempted to recover.
[src:1906-chicago-cubs-season/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] The team would not resurface until 1874.
[src:1906-chicago-cubs-season/1874-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1874 Chicago White Stockings season** was the third season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the second in the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players and the first at 23rd Street Grounds.
[src:1906-chicago-cubs-season/1874-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings returned to the league in 1874 after taking two years to recover from the chaos of the Great Chicago Fire.
[src:1906-chicago-cubs-season/1874-chicago-white-stockings-season] They opened their season on Wednesday May 13 hosting the Philadelphia Athletics and shut them out 4 to 0.
[src:1906-chicago-cubs-season/1874-chicago-white-stockings-season] They finished fifth in the National Association with a record of 28–31.
[src:1906-chicago-cubs-season/1874-major-league-baseball-season] The following are the baseball events of the year 1874 throughout the world.
[src:1906-chicago-cubs-season/1875-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1875 Chicago White Stockings season** was the fourth season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the third and final in the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players and the second at 23rd Street Grounds.
[src:1906-chicago-cubs-season/1875-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings finished sixth in the National Association with a record of 30–37–2.
[src:1906-chicago-cubs-season/1876-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1876 Chicago White Stockings season** was the fifth season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the first in the National League and the third at 23rd Street Grounds.
[src:1906-chicago-cubs-season/1876-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings, as one of the founding members of the new National League, won the NL's initial championship during this season with a record of 52–14.
[src:1906-chicago-cubs-season/1877-boston-red-caps-season] The **1877 Boston Red Caps season** was the seventh season of the franchise.
[src:1906-chicago-cubs-season/1877-boston-red-caps-season] Arthur Soden became the new owner of the franchise, who won their first National League pennant.
[src:1906-chicago-cubs-season/1877-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1877 Chicago White Stockings season** was the 6th season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the 2nd in the National League and the fourth at 23rd Street Grounds.
[src:1906-chicago-cubs-season/1877-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings finished fifth in the National League with a record of 26–33.
[src:1906-chicago-cubs-season/1906-chicago-cubs-season] The **1906 Chicago Cubs season** was the 35th season of the Chicago Cubs franchise, the 31st in the National League and the 14th at West Side Park.
[src:1906-chicago-cubs-season/1906-chicago-cubs-season] Skippered by player-manager Frank Chance, the Cubs won the National League pennant with a record of 116–36, a full 20 games ahead of the second-place New York Giants.
[src:1906-chicago-cubs-season/1906-chicago-cubs-season] The team's .763 winning percentage, with two ties in their 154-game season, is the highest in modern MLB history.
[src:1906-chicago-cubs-season/1906-chicago-cubs-season] The 2001 Seattle Mariners also won 116 games, but they did that in 162 games, resulting in a .716 winning percentage.
[src:1906-chicago-cubs-season/1906-chicago-cubs-season] The 1906 Cubs are often considered the greatest MLB team to not win the World Series.
[src:1906-chicago-cubs-season/1906-chicago-cubs-season] In a major upset, the Cubs were beaten by their crosstown counterparts Chicago White Sox in that year's World Series.
[src:1906-chicago-cubs-season/1906-chicago-cubs-season] Led by new manager Frank Chance, the Cubs dominated the NL.
[src:1906-chicago-cubs-season/1906-chicago-cubs-season] They led the league in both runs scored and fewest runs allowed by large margins.
[src:1906-chicago-cubs-season/1906-chicago-cubs-season] Their record of 116 wins has never been beaten, although it was tied by the 2001 Seattle Mariners (who played a longer 162-game season).
[src:1906-chicago-cubs-season/1906-chicago-cubs-season] The team included four future Hall of Famers: manager and first baseman Chance, second baseman Johnny Evers, shortstop Joe Tinker, and pitcher Mordecai Brown.
[src:1906-chicago-cubs-season/1906-chicago-cubs-season] Brown finished second in the NL in wins to Joe McGinnity, but his 1.04 ERA set a major league record.
[src:1906-chicago-cubs-season/1906-chicago-cubs-season] Although the record was broken by Dutch Leonard in 1914, Brown's mark still stands as the National League record.
[src:1906-chicago-cubs-season/1906-chicago-cubs-season] The pitching staff led the majors with a team earned run average of 1.75.
[src:1906-chicago-cubs-season/1906-chicago-cubs-season] Six members of the pitching staff had double digit victories – Mordecai Brown (26), Jack Pfiester (20), Ed Reulbach (19), Carl Lundgren (17), Orval Overall (12), and Jack Taylor (12).
[src:1906-chicago-cubs-season/1906-chicago-cubs-season] In addition, Mordecai Brown set a major league record with the lowest earned run average attained with at least 250 innings pitched (1.04).
[src:1906-chicago-cubs-season/1906-chicago-cubs-season] The offensive star was third baseman Harry Steinfeldt, who led the NL in both hits and RBI.
[src:1906-chicago-cubs-season/1906-chicago-cubs-season] The team's .763 winning percentage also set a modern-era record, and was the best overall since 1885.
[src:1906-chicago-cubs-season/1906-chicago-cubs-season] However, it set neither a National League record nor even a franchise record, as the 19th-century White Stockings finished with better records on three occasions (1876, 1880, and 1885).
[src:1906-chicago-cubs-season/1906-chicago-cubs-season] The all-time major league record belongs to the 1884 St.
[src:1906-chicago-cubs-season/1906-chicago-cubs-season] Louis Maroons of the Union Association at .832.
[src:1906-chicago-cubs-season/1906-chicago-cubs-season] On August 9, Jack Taylor threw the last of a major league record 187 consecutive complete games that he pitched (not counting appearances as a relief pitcher), a streak that began in 1901 when Taylor was pitching for the Chicago Orphans.
[src:1906-chicago-cubs-season/1906-chicago-cubs-season] Taylor had been re-acquired from the St.
[src:1906-chicago-cubs-season/1906-chicago-cubs-season] Louis Cardinals on July 1, having been traded to the Cards after the 1903 season.
